      "locked": false,
      "text": "Interview Cross Question\n\nPerfect 😄\nI’ll act like the **interviewer**, you answer in your head, and then I’ll give you the **ideal crisp answer** they expect.\nThis is *exactly* how these rounds go.\n\n---\n\n# 🔥 WSGI vs ASGI — Cross Questions (with Model Answers)\n\n---\n\n## ❓ Q1: *“If ASGI can handle multiple requests in one worker, why do we still need multiple workers?”*\n\n### What interviewer is testing\n\n* Do you understand **CPU vs I/O**\n* Do you think async = infinite scalability?\n\n### 💡 Ideal Answer\n\n> Async only helps with **I/O-bound concurrency**.\n> CPU-bound tasks still block the event loop.\n> Multiple workers are needed to:\n>\n> * use multiple CPU cores\n> * isolate crashes\n> * handle CPU-heavy requests\n\n> So we usually run **multiple async workers**, not just one.\n\n---\n\n## ❓ Q2: *“Can async/await make Django faster automatically?”*\n\n### Wrong answer 🚫\n\n“Yes, async is faster”\n\n### 💡 Ideal Answer\n\n> No. Async only improves performance when:\n>\n> * the code is I/O-heavy\n> * dependencies (DB drivers, HTTP clients) are async\n\n> If Django code uses sync ORM or blocking libraries, async gives **no benefit**.\n\n🔥 Bonus line:\n\n> Async without async dependencies is just syntax, not concurrency.\n\n---\n\n## ❓ Q3: *“What happens if I use `time.sleep()` inside an async view?”*\n\n### What they want\n\n* Event loop understanding\n\n### 💡 Ideal Answer\n\n> `time.sleep()` blocks the entire event loop.\n> This freezes **all concurrent requests** in that worker.\n\n> We must use `await asyncio.sleep()` instead.\n\n---\n\n## ❓ Q4: *“Why is FastAPI generally faster than Django?”*\n\n### Real reason (not hype)\n\n> FastAPI is async-first, minimal middleware, and uses:\n>\n> * Starlette (lightweight ASGI framework)\n> * Pydantic for fast validation\n> * Uvicorn with event loop\n\n> Django has:\n>\n> * heavier middleware stack\n> * mostly synchronous ORM\n> * backward compatibility constraints\n\n---\n\n## ❓ Q5: *“If async is so good, why doesn’t Django fully switch to async?”*\n\n### Gold-standard answer 🏆\n\n> Django is a mature framework with:\n>\n> * massive ecosystem\n> * mostly synchronous ORM\n> * backward compatibility guarantees\n\n> Making everything async would break:\n>\n> * third-party packages\n> * existing applications\n\n> So Django supports **hybrid async**, not full async.\n\n---\n\n## ❓ Q6: *“How does Gunicorn decide how many workers to run?”*\n\n### Expected formula\n\n> A common rule of thumb is:\n\n```text\nworkers = (2 × CPU cores) + 1\n```\n\nBut…\n\n### Better answer:\n\n> It depends on:\n>\n> * CPU vs I/O workload\n> * memory availability\n> * request duration\n\n> Async servers often need **fewer workers** than WSGI.\n\n---\n\n## ❓ Q7: *“Can ASGI replace Celery?”*\n\n### Trap question 🚨\n\n### 💡 Ideal Answer\n\n> No.\n> ASGI handles concurrent requests, not background execution.\n\n> Long-running tasks should still go to:\n>\n> * Celery\n> * RQ\n> * Background workers\n\n> ASGI is for **request lifecycle**, not job queues.\n\n---\n\n## ❓ Q8: *“Explain request flow in FastAPI from client to response.”*\n\n### Perfect flow answer\n\n> Client → Uvicorn → Event Loop → ASGI app\n> → async endpoint\n> → await I/O\n> → response sent back via event loop\n\nKeep it short. No overengineering.\n\n---\n\n## ❓ Q9: *“What happens if one async request crashes?”*\n\n### Good answer\n\n> It affects only that coroutine.\n> Other requests in the event loop continue running.\n> But if the **worker process crashes**, all its requests die.\n\nThat shows **process vs coroutine isolation knowledge**.\n\n---\n\n## ❓ Q10: *“When would you choose WSGI over ASGI?”*\n\n### Strong practical answer\n\n> I’d choose WSGI when:\n>\n> * app is mostly CPU-bound\n> * legacy Django project\n> * no heavy concurrent I/O\n> * simpler deployment preferred\n\n> ASGI when:\n>\n> * real-time APIs\n> * WebSockets\n> * high concurrent I/O\n\n---\n\n## 🎯 Final Interview Power Summary (memorize this)\n\n> “WSGI relies on OS-level parallelism using multiple processes, while ASGI uses an event loop to multiplex I/O-bound requests inside a worker. Async improves throughput for I/O-heavy workloads but does not replace multi-process scaling.”\n\n---\n\n\n",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Interview Cross Question\n\nPerfect 😄\nI’ll act like the **interviewer**, you answer in your head, and then I’ll give you the **ideal crisp answer** they expect.\nThis is *exactly* how these rounds go.\n\n---\n\n# 🔥 WSGI vs ASGI — Cross Questions (with Model Answers)\n\n---\n\n## ❓ Q1: *“If ASGI can handle multiple requests in one worker, why do we still need multiple workers?”*\n\n### What interviewer is testing\n\n* Do you understand **CPU vs I/O**\n* Do you think async = infinite scalability?\n\n### 💡 Ideal Answer\n\n> Async only helps with **I/O-bound concurrency**.\n> CPU-bound tasks still block the event loop.\n> Multiple workers are needed to:\n>\n> * use multiple CPU cores\n> * isolate crashes\n> * handle CPU-heavy requests\n\n> So we usually run **multiple async workers**, not just one.\n\n---\n\n## ❓ Q2: *“Can async/await make Django faster automatically?”*\n\n### Wrong answer 🚫\n\n“Yes, async is faster”\n\n### 💡 Ideal Answer\n\n> No. Async only improves performance when:\n>\n> * the code is I/O-heavy\n> * dependencies (DB drivers, HTTP clients) are async\n\n> If Django code uses sync ORM or blocking libraries, async gives **no benefit**.\n\n🔥 Bonus line:\n\n> Async without async dependencies is just syntax, not concurrency.\n\n---\n\n## ❓ Q3: *“What happens if I use `time.sleep()` inside an async view?”*\n\n### What they want\n\n* Event loop understanding\n\n### 💡 Ideal Answer\n\n> `time.sleep()` blocks the entire event loop.\n> This freezes **all concurrent requests** in that worker.\n\n> We must use `await asyncio.sleep()` instead.\n\n---\n\n## ❓ Q4: *“Why is FastAPI generally faster than Django?”*\n\n### Real reason (not hype)\n\n> FastAPI is async-first, minimal middleware, and uses:\n>\n> * Starlette (lightweight ASGI framework)\n> * Pydantic for fast validation\n> * Uvicorn with event loop\n\n> Django has:\n>\n> * heavier middleware stack\n> * mostly synchronous ORM\n> * backward compatibility constraints\n\n---\n\n## ❓ Q5: *“If async is so good, why doesn’t Django fully switch to async?”*\n\n### Gold-standard answer 🏆\n\n> Django is a mature framework with:\n>\n> * massive ecosystem\n> * mostly synchronous ORM\n> * backward compatibility guarantees\n\n> Making everything async would break:\n>\n> * third-party packages\n> * existing applications\n\n> So Django supports **hybrid async**, not full async.\n\n---\n\n## ❓ Q6: *“How does Gunicorn decide how many workers to run?”*\n\n### Expected formula\n\n> A common rule of thumb is:\n\n```text\nworkers = (2 × CPU cores) + 1\n```\n\nBut…\n\n### Better answer:\n\n> It depends on:\n>\n> * CPU vs I/O workload\n> * memory availability\n> * request duration\n\n> Async servers often need **fewer workers** than WSGI.\n\n---\n\n## ❓ Q7: *“Can ASGI replace Celery?”*\n\n### Trap question 🚨\n\n### 💡 Ideal Answer\n\n> No.\n> ASGI handles concurrent requests, not background execution.\n\n> Long-running tasks should still go to:\n>\n> * Celery\n> * RQ\n> * Background workers\n\n> ASGI is for **request lifecycle**, not job queues.\n\n---\n\n## ❓ Q8: *“Explain request flow in FastAPI from client to response.”*\n\n### Perfect flow answer\n\n> Client → Uvicorn → Event Loop → ASGI app\n> → async endpoint\n> → await I/O\n> → response sent back via event loop\n\nKeep it short. No overengineering.\n\n---\n\n## ❓ Q9: *“What happens if one async request crashes?”*\n\n### Good answer\n\n> It affects only that coroutine.\n> Other requests in the event loop continue running.\n> But if the **worker process crashes**, all its requests die.\n\nThat shows **process vs coroutine isolation knowledge**.\n\n---\n\n## ❓ Q10: *“When would you choose WSGI over ASGI?”*\n\n### Strong practical answer\n\n> I’d choose WSGI when:\n>\n> * app is mostly CPU-bound\n> * legacy Django project\n> * no heavy concurrent I/O\n> * simpler deployment preferred\n\n> ASGI when:\n>\n> * real-time APIs\n> * WebSockets\n> * high concurrent I/O\n\n---\n\n## 🎯 Final Interview Power Summary (memorize this)\n\n> “WSGI relies on OS-level parallelism using multiple processes, while ASGI uses an event loop to multiplex I/O-bound requests inside a worker. Async improves throughput for I/O-heavy workloads but does not replace multi-process scaling.”\n\n---\n\n\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
