      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1775226521877,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Short answer: **it depends on sync vs async**—but this is exactly the confusion most people have.\n\n---\n\n# 🔹 In a single worker, what really happens?\n\n## ✅ 1. **Synchronous (Blocking) worker**\n\nExample: traditional Django (WSGI), Flask\n\n👉 **Only ONE request runs at a time per worker thread**\n\n```\nWorker:\n[Request A running] → finished\n[Request B starts] → finished\n```\n\n* If Request A is waiting (DB/API call) → worker is **idle but blocked**\n* No other request can run in that thread\n\n👉 To handle multiple requests:\n\n* You need **multiple workers/threads**\n\n---\n\n## ⚡ 2. **Asynchronous (FastAPI / ASGI)**\n\nBuilt on:\n\n* ASGI\n* Uvicorn\n\n👉 **One worker CAN handle multiple requests concurrently**\n\nBUT ⚠️ important nuance:\n\n> Not truly parallel execution — it's **cooperative multitasking**\n\n---\n\n## 🔁 What actually happens inside one async worker\n\n```\nWorker (1 thread, event loop):\n\nRequest A → waiting (DB/API)\n          ↘ switch\nRequest B → waiting\n          ↘ switch\nRequest C → processing\n```\n\n👉 So:\n\n* At a **single instant** → only one piece of code executes\n* But during waiting → it **switches between requests**\n\n---\n\n## 🧠 So what's the correct statement?\n\n👉 **Not this:**\n\n> \"Multiple requests run at the same time in one worker\"\n\n👉 **Correct:**\n\n> \"One worker handles multiple requests concurrently by switching during I/O waits\"\n\n---\n\n## 🔥 Simple analogy\n\nOne chef 🍳:\n\n* Sync → waits for one dish to cook fully before next\n* Async → puts dish A in oven, starts dish B, then C\n\n👉 Chef is still ONE\n👉 But many dishes progress together\n\n---\n\n## 🔹 Important distinction\n\n| Concept     | Meaning                                             |\n| ----------- | --------------------------------------------------- |\n| Concurrency | Handling multiple tasks by switching                |\n| Parallelism | Running multiple tasks at same time (multiple CPUs) |\n\n👉 Async = **Concurrency**\n👉 Multiple workers/cores = **Parallelism**\n\n---\n\n## 🔹 What if requests are CPU-heavy?\n\nEven in FastAPI:\n\n```\nRequest A (CPU heavy)\n→ blocks event loop ❌\n→ no switching happens\n```\n\n👉 Then:\n\n* Only one request truly runs\n* Others wait\n\n---\n\n## 🔹 Real-world setup (production)\n\nYou combine both:\n\n```\nMultiple workers (parallelism)\n+\nAsync inside each worker (concurrency)\n```\n\nExample:\n\n* 4 workers × each handles 1000 concurrent I/O requests\n\n---\n\n## 🧠 Final takeaway\n\n👉 **One async worker:**\n\n* Executes **one instruction at a time**\n* Handles **many requests concurrently via non-blocking I/O**\n\n👉 **Multiple workers:**\n\n* Enable **true parallel execution**\n\n---\n\nIf you want, I can next:\n\n* Draw **exact request lifecycle inside FastAPI (event loop, coroutine scheduling)**\n* Or compare **Gunicorn + Uvicorn workers vs Django workers** (very common interview question)\n",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Short answer: **it depends on sync vs async**—but this is exactly the confusion most people have.\n\n---\n\n# 🔹 In a single worker, what really happens?\n\n## ✅ 1. **Synchronous (Blocking) worker**\n\nExample: traditional Django (WSGI), Flask\n\n👉 **Only ONE request runs at a time per worker thread**\n\n```\nWorker:\n[Request A running] → finished\n[Request B starts] → finished\n```\n\n* If Request A is waiting (DB/API call) → worker is **idle but blocked**\n* No other request can run in that thread\n\n👉 To handle multiple requests:\n\n* You need **multiple workers/threads**\n\n---\n\n## ⚡ 2. **Asynchronous (FastAPI / ASGI)**\n\nBuilt on:\n\n* ASGI\n* Uvicorn\n\n👉 **One worker CAN handle multiple requests concurrently**\n\nBUT ⚠️ important nuance:\n\n> Not truly parallel execution — it's **cooperative multitasking**\n\n---\n\n## 🔁 What actually happens inside one async worker\n\n```\nWorker (1 thread, event loop):\n\nRequest A → waiting (DB/API)\n          ↘ switch\nRequest B → waiting\n          ↘ switch\nRequest C → processing\n```\n\n👉 So:\n\n* At a **single instant** → only one piece of code executes\n* But during waiting → it **switches between requests**\n\n---\n\n## 🧠 So what's the correct statement?\n\n👉 **Not this:**\n\n> \"Multiple requests run at the same time in one worker\"\n\n👉 **Correct:**\n\n> \"One worker handles multiple requests concurrently by switching during I/O waits\"\n\n---\n\n## 🔥 Simple analogy\n\nOne chef 🍳:\n\n* Sync → waits for one dish to cook fully before next\n* Async → puts dish A in oven, starts dish B, then C\n\n👉 Chef is still ONE\n👉 But many dishes progress together\n\n---\n\n## 🔹 Important distinction\n\n| Concept     | Meaning                                             |\n| ----------- | --------------------------------------------------- |\n| Concurrency | Handling multiple tasks by switching                |\n| Parallelism | Running multiple tasks at same time (multiple CPUs) |\n\n👉 Async = **Concurrency**\n👉 Multiple workers/cores = **Parallelism**\n\n---\n\n## 🔹 What if requests are CPU-heavy?\n\nEven in FastAPI:\n\n```\nRequest A (CPU heavy)\n→ blocks event loop ❌\n→ no switching happens\n```\n\n👉 Then:\n\n* Only one request truly runs\n* Others wait\n\n---\n\n## 🔹 Real-world setup (production)\n\nYou combine both:\n\n```\nMultiple workers (parallelism)\n+\nAsync inside each worker (concurrency)\n```\n\nExample:\n\n* 4 workers × each handles 1000 concurrent I/O requests\n\n---\n\n## 🧠 Final takeaway\n\n👉 **One async worker:**\n\n* Executes **one instruction at a time**\n* Handles **many requests concurrently via non-blocking I/O**\n\n👉 **Multiple workers:**\n\n* Enable **true parallel execution**\n\n---\n\nIf you want, I can next:\n\n* Draw **exact request lifecycle inside FastAPI (event loop, coroutine scheduling)**\n* Or compare **Gunicorn + Uvicorn workers vs Django workers** (very common interview question)\n",
